{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "# 🤖 Chapter 1: Introduction to Machine Learning\n",
    "**Reference:** *Introduction to Machine Learning with Python: A Guide for Data Scientists* by Andreas C. Müller & Sarah Guido\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 1.1 What is Machine Learning?\n",
    "Machine Learning (ML) is the field of study that gives computers the ability to learn without being explicitly programmed. It is a subset of Artificial Intelligence (AI) that focuses on building systems that learn from past experience (data) to make predictions or decisions about the future.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why Machine Learning Over Traditional Programming?\n",
    "In traditional programming, a human expert writes explicit rules (if-then statements) to process data and produce an output. However, this approach fails dramatically when:\n",
    "1. **The rules are too complex to define manually:** For example, face recognition or speech-to-text transformation.\n",
    "2. **The logic changes over time:** For example, spam filtering where spammers constantly adapt their email phrasing.\n",
    "\n",
    "Machine learning turns this paradigm upside down: we feed the system data and the expected outputs, and the algorithm organically discovers the underlying rules and patterns."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "## 1.2 Core Concepts: Supervised vs. Unsupervised Learning\n",
    "Most machine learning applications fall into one of two main categories:\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1. Supervised Learning\n",
    "In supervised learning, the user provides the algorithm with pairs of inputs (features) and expected outputs (labels). The algorithm learns a mapping from inputs to outputs so that when it is given a new, unseen input, it can accurately predict the correct output.\n",
    "- **Classification:** Predicting a discrete class label or category (e.g., identifying whether an email is 'Spam' or 'Not Spam', or classifying a tumor as 'Benign' or 'Malignant').\n",
    "- **Regression:** Predicting a continuous numerical value (e.g., predicting house prices based on square footage, or forecasting stock returns).\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2. Unsupervised Learning\n",
    "In unsupervised learning, the algorithm is given only the input data, with no explicit target labels. The algorithm must find structure, groupings, or patterns within the data on its own.\n",
    "- **Clustering:** Grouping similar data points together (e.g., customer segmentation for targeted marketing).\n",
    "- **Dimensionality Reduction:** Compressing high-dimensional data into fewer features while preserving crucial information (e.g., PCA for data visualization)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import sklearn\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"NumPy version      : {np.__version__}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Pandas version     : {pd.__version__}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Scikit-learn version: {sklearn.__version__}\")\n",
    "print(\"\\nCore data science toolkit successfully loaded.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "## 1.3 Knowing Your Data: Important Pre-modeling Questions\n",
    "Before blindly feeding data into a Scikit-learn model, the authors emphasize that you must perform comprehensive Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and ask yourself:\n",
    "- What question am I trying to answer? Does my available data actually contain enough signal to answer it?\n",
    "- What is the best way to phrase my problem as a machine learning task (e.g., binary classification, multi-class classification, or regression)?\n",
    "- Did I collect enough data to capture the real-world variance of the problem?\n",
    "- How did I measure my features? Are there missing values or corrupt data points that require preprocessing?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "## 1.4 A First Application: Classifying Iris Species\n",
    "To introduce the absolute mechanics of building a supervised machine learning model using Scikit-learn, the authors walk through a classic dataset: the **Iris dataset** collected by botanist Edgar Anderson and popularized by Ronald Fisher.\n",
    "\n",
    "### The Problem\n",
    "We want to build a machine learning model that takes physical measurements of an iris flower and automatically predicts its specific species.\n",
    "- **Features (Inputs):** Sepal length, Sepal width, Petal length, Petal width (all measured in centimeters).\n",
    "- **Target Labels (Outputs):** The species name, which can be one of three options: *Setosa*, *Versicolor*, or *Virginica*. This is a **three-class classification problem**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.datasets import load_iris\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load the dataset dictionary\n",
    "iris_dataset = load_iris()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Explore the structural keys provided in the scikit-learn Bunch object\n",
    "print(\"Keys of iris_dataset:\")\n",
    "print(iris_dataset.keys())\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\nTarget names (Classes to predict): {iris_dataset['target_names']}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Feature names (Predictor dimensions): {iris_dataset['feature_names']}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Shape of data matrix (Rows x Columns): {iris_dataset['data'].shape}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "## 1.5 Understanding Training and Testing Data\n",
    "We cannot evaluate the performance of our model using the exact same data we used to train it. Why? Because a model can simply memorize the training set (overfitting), making it appear highly accurate, but it will fail completely when deployed to predict on new, unseen flowers in the real world.\n",
    "\n",
    "To solve this, we use Scikit-learn's `train_test_split` function to divide our dataset into two distinct buckets:\n",
    "- **Training Set (75% of data):** Used to teach the model how features map to labels.\n",
    "- **Test Set (25% of data):** Held out securely. Once the model is fully trained, we ask it to predict on this test data and check its accuracy against the true labels."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
    "\n",
    "# X represents the feature data matrix (2D array)\n",
    "# y represents the target label vector (1D array)\n",
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\n",
    "    iris_dataset['data'], \n",
    "    iris_dataset['target'], \n",
    "    test_size=0.25,        # 25% for testing, 75% for training\n",
    "    random_state=0         # Fixed seed for perfect reproducibility\n")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"X_train shape: {X_train.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"y_train shape: {y_train.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"X_test shape : {X_test.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"y_test shape : {y_test.shape}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "## 1.6 Visualizing the Data (Pair Plots)\n",
    "Before building a model, it is critical to look at the data visually. Doing so helps you identify extreme outliers, skewed features, and determine if the classes are actually separable.\n",
    "\n",
    "For multi-dimensional numeric data, a **Pair Plot (Scatter Plot Matrix)** is the best tool. It draws a scatter plot for every possible pair of features in the dataset. If the different species clump into separate clusters in these plots, it tells us that a machine learning classifier will likely be highly successful."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "\n",
    "# Convert the training array into a Pandas DataFrame for plotting\n",
    "iris_dataframe = pd.DataFrame(X_train, columns=iris_dataset.feature_names)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add the target labels to the dataframe\n",
    "iris_dataframe['species'] = y_train\n",
    "iris_dataframe['species'] = iris_dataframe['species'].map({\n",
    "    0: iris_dataset['target_names'][0],\n",
    "    1: iris_dataset['target_names'][1],\n",
    "    2: iris_dataset['target_names'][2]\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generate the pair plot using Seaborn\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))\n",
    "sns.pairplot(iris_dataframe, hue='species', markers=['o', 's', 'D'], palette='muted')\n",
    "plt.suptitle(\"Pair Plot of Iris Training Data\", y=1.02)\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Observation: The species form distinct, highly separated clusters, especially when looking at petal length and petal width. This confirms the data contains strong predictive signals.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "## 1.7 Building the Model: K-Nearest Neighbors\n",
    "The authors introduce **K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)** as our first classifier because it is incredibly intuitive. \n",
    "\n",
    "To classify a brand new flower:\n",
    "1. The algorithm measures the physical distance (Euclidean space) from the new flower to every single flower in our training set.\n",
    "2. It finds the $K$ closest training instances (e.g., if $K=1$, it looks for the single nearest neighbor).\n",
    "3. It assigns the new flower to whatever class the majority of those neighbors belong to.\n",
    "\n",
    "All Scikit-learn estimators follow a uniform interface. We instantiate the class, and then call the `.fit()` method to pass our training data and build the internal model structures."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier\n",
    "\n",
    "# Instantiate the estimator class. We choose 1 nearest neighbor (K=1)\n",
    "knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Train the model by calling .fit()\n",
    "knn.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(knn)\n",
    "print(\"\\nModel successfully instantiated and trained using the scikit-learn workflow.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "## 1.8 Making Predictions\n",
    "Now that our model is trained, we can pass completely new flower measurements into its `.predict()` method to see what class it assigns."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Imagine we found a new iris flower in the wild with the following dimensions:\n",
    "# Sepal length = 5cm, Sepal width = 2.9cm, Petal length = 1cm, Petal width = 0.2cm\n",
    "# Scikit-learn always expects inputs as a 2D array, so we wrap it in a nested list\n",
    "X_new = np.array([[5, 2.9, 1, 0.2]])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generate the prediction\n",
    "prediction = knn.predict(X_new)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Predicted target class index: {prediction[0]}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Predicted species name       : {iris_dataset['target_names'][prediction[0]]}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "## 1.9 Evaluating the Model\n",
    "To measure how robust our model truly is, we predict on the complete **test set** (`X_test`) that we held out earlier. We then measure the **Accuracy Score**—the percentage of flowers the model classified perfectly."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Generate predictions for the entire test set\n",
    "y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Method 1: Using NumPy to compare prediction vector with true test labels\n",
    "accuracy_manual = np.mean(y_pred == y_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Method 2: Using the built-in .score() method of the estimator object\n",
    "accuracy_score_obj = knn.score(X_test, y_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Test set score (Manual NumPy)  : {accuracy_manual:.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Test set score (knn.score obj) : {accuracy_score_obj:.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nOur model is {accuracy_score_obj*100:.1f}% accurate on completely unseen data!\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "## 1.10 Chapter Summary\n",
    "Key takeaways from Chapter 1:\n",
    "1. **Supervised learning tasks** require pairs of input features and distinct ground-truth labels.\n",
    "2. **Data Splitting (`train_test_split`)** is non-negotiable. Evaluating a model on the data used to train it creates a dangerous illusion of success due to overfitting.\n",
    "3. **Scikit-learn API consistency:** All algorithms follow a modular pipeline: instantiate model -> call `.fit()` to train -> call `.predict()` to evaluate.\n",
    "4. **Visual verification (Pair plots)** must always be performed before applying mathematical models to gain geometric intuition about feature behaviors."
   ]
  }
 ],
 "nbformat": 4,
